Barclays, British Land, IAG: U.K., Irish Equity Market Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   J u l i e   C r u z
-- 
2011-06-08T06:30:27Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-07/barclays-british-land-iag-u-k-irish-equity-market-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The FTSE 100 Index rose 1.49 points, or less than 0.1
percent, to 5,864.65 yesterday. The FTSE All-Share Index gained
less than 0.1 percent to 3,064.03. Ireland’s ISEQ declined 0.5
percent to 2,924.76.  Barclays Plc (BARC)  : The U.K. bank that bought Lehman
Brothers Holdings Inc.’s North American business must return $2
billion in margin assets to the trustee liquidating the remains
of Lehman’s brokerage and pay about $270 million in interest, a
bankruptcy judge ruled. The shares dropped 0.6 percent to 262.55
pence.  British Land Co. (BLND LN): The U.K.’s second-largest real
estate investment trust said it signed a 560 million-pound ($921
million) loan to refinance existing debt. The stock gained 0.2
percent to 593 pence.  Hyder Consulting Plc (HYC)  : The engineering-design
company said net income rose to 14.9 million pounds for the year
ended March 31, from 11.2 million pounds a year earlier. The
shares added 0.5 percent to 387 pence.  International Consolidated Airlines Group SA (IAG LN):
IAG’s British Airways and Chilean carrier Lan Airlines SA agreed
to pay a total of $155.5 million to cargo customers to settle a
U.S. lawsuit over their involvement in a global price-fixing
cartel that increased fuel surcharges. The stock fell 0.2
percent to 229.1 pence.  Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc (RBS)  : The U.K.’s
biggest government-controlled bank plans to expand operations in
 China  and rebuild its Asian equity capital markets unit after
the workforce at its corporate and investment banking operations
in the region dropped last year. The shares retreated 0.2
percent to 41.39 pence.  SThree Plc (STHR)  : The U.K. recruiting company founded
as Computer Futures in 1986 said its gross profit rose 23
percent to about 90 million pounds in the six months ended May
29 from a year earlier, excluding currency effects. The shares
dropped 2.9 percent to 393.4 pence.  Victrex Plc (VCT)  : The maker of heat-resistant plastics
for the automotive and energy industries will likely see more
takeover interest, according to Goldman Sachs Group Inc., which
included a 10 percent premium for mergers and acquisitions in
its price target for the British plastics maker. The shares
gained 1.9 percent to 1,445 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
